<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-517-701  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 517 701.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Oct 8 1990 v7 n11 p90(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>8mm offers more space in smaller packages:cost less than 1 centper megabyte of storage. (part of a special section on back-uptape technologies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Beavers, Kelly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Helical-scan tape recording techniques offer higher datacapacities in a smaller physical package than any other computerstorage technology.andP;  Other benefits include low power consumption,low cost, and high reliability.andP;  Helical-scan products can back upextremely large files or even entire systems to a single,pocket-sized cartridge.andP;  Digital audio tape (DAT) and 8mm are thetwo chief helical scan formats used for data storage.andP;  8mm offerscertain advantages over DAT.andP;  A full-width stationary head erasesthe tape during 8mm write operations, eliminating residual servoand data signals that can corrupt data or interfere with datainterchange.andP;  Additionally, 8mm has a much shorter start-stoprepositioning (SSR) latency period than DAT.andP;  8mm tape also offershigher performance at a much lower areal density, 35Mb/in2 to74Mb/in2, compared to 114Mb/in2 for DAT, very near the upper limitof 120Mb/in2.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Helical-Scan TechnologyTape DrivesPerformanceHigh TechnologyHardware SelectionBack-Up Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   DAT minimum writable unit. (chart)Comparison of 8mm and 4mm tape technologies. (table)Three sequential search methods for finding records on digitalaudio tape. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>